[Student "E"]
{[showcards S:DJ W:D2 N:D4]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \HQ, you played low and North won the \HA.

North now plays the \DJ on which East plays the \D2. What do you play now, and what is your plan.

Play the \D3 and when North plays another \D win with your \DA.

South hoped his \D suit would provide enough tricks to make the game. You can see that there is no entry to the South hand EXCEPT in \Ds, so you want to win your \DA on the trick that North plays his last \D. How can you tell which trick that is?

Only by watching what East plays. On the \DJ East played the \D2, a low card signaling that he held an ODD number of \Ds. ODD must be either one or three so when he followed to the next \D you know he started with three. A little bit of counting tells you that North started with the doubleton Jack, so you want to win the second \D trick.

This defense holds North to one \D tricks, if you had let him win the second one he would have had 9 tricks. }
[Play "W"]HQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:JT4.AK3.JT9.AKQJ A65.QT64.K72.T52 KQ93.87.Q65.9764 872.J952.A843.83"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1C pass 1S pass 2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "41f3c0febd8580324452c9fe8df6f249c8b22dcc16b7292a2dc1c106b484928d"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/defensive_signals"]
[Student "W"]
{[showcards S:ST]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown. You led the \H4, North plays the \HJ, won by East with \HA.

East plays the \SJ, you follow with \S5, dummy \S3 and North plays the \S2. East continues with the \ST 

Play the \S6.

North's \S2 tells you he had an ODD number of \Ss, obviously 3. Since East also must have 3, you must take your \SA on the third round, depriving dummy of the extra \S trick.

East may now turn to the \D suit, but your side can win the first \D and drive out East's \HK. You will win 2 \Hs, 2 \Ds and the \SA, down 1}
[Play "W"]H4

